{"commit_hash":"60216b989ce5c51ccae7e2ab93f4ad0ef8518a8b","commit_message":"feat(deamon): add global lifecycle","branch":"deamon-lifecycle","timestamp":"2026-03-01T14:12:48+01:00","files_changed":["CLAUDE.md","Cargo.lock","README.md","src/cli/init.rs","src/cli/ls.rs","src/cli/mod.rs","src/cli/restart.rs","src/cli/rm.rs","src/cli/start.rs","src/cli/stop.rs","src/daemon/mod.rs","src/daemon/registry.rs","src/error.rs","src/main.rs"],"decisions":[{"title":"Chose a global daemon registry over per-project scoping","summary":"The goal was to give users a single view of all daemons, similar to how Docker lists containers, so that commands could be issued from any directory. The discussion weighed keeping the existing per‑project registry against adding a new file in the user’s home directory. A global TOML file was selected because it is human‑editable, easy to parse with `toml` and fits the existing `~/.shadw` config layout.\n\nThe implementation introduced a `DaemonRegistry` struct that loads the TOML file on demand, writes atomically via a temp file, and exposes helpers for registering, unregistering, and resolving targets. The registry is used by the new `ls`, `rm`, `start`, `stop`, and `restart` commands, which now accept an `<id|path|all>` argument. The registry also tracks daemon status and uptime, enabling the `ls` command to display a concise table.\n\nKey technical choices include using `serde::Deserialize`/`Serialize` for the registry, storing entries as `DaemonEntry` with fields for path, pid, status, and timestamps, and providing a `RegistryTarget` enum to parse user input. The registry file lives at `~/.shadw/daemons.toml`, and the code ensures it is created on first use. The new commands are wired into `main.rs` and documented in the README and CLAUDE.md. All tests pass, confirming the new global view works without breaking existing functionality."}],"extracted_at":"2026-03-01T13:12:55.514708+00:00","model":"gpt-oss"}
